Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa on Sunday travelled to Davos in Switzerland where he will lead a high-level government, business, and labour delegation to the 2017 World Economic Forum (WEF) annual meeting from January 17 to 20, the presidency said. Organised under the theme Responsive and Responsible Leadership , this year s WEF, taking place against the background of a challenging global environment, was expected to attract over 2700 world leaders in the public and private sectors to discuss the global economy, Ramaphosa s spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa said in a statement. The programme for the annual event had been organised around five areas which had been identified as in need of urgent responsive and responsible leadership, namely preparing for the fourth industrial revolution, strengthening systems for global collaboration, revitalising the global economy, and reforming market capitalism and addressing identity through positive narratives . The South African team under the leadership of Ramaphosa would communicate to the global community the positive message that working together, our future is in our hands , Mamoepa said. In this context the South African team would use the opportunity presented by the WEF to highlight the work government, working together with business and labour, was doing to implement economic transformation and the reform agenda, make progress towards achieving inclusive growth and employment, restore investor confidence, achieve supportive business confidence, and refine government spending efficiency, he said. Ramaphosa s government delegation includes Finance Minister Pravin Gordhan, Minister in the Presidency for Planning, Monitoring, and Evaluation Jeff Radebe, Trade and Industry Minister Rob Davies, Economic Development Minister Ebrahim Patel, Water and Sanitation Minister Nomvula Mokonyane, and KwaZulu-Natal economic development, tourism, and environmental affairs MEC Sihle Zikalala. African News Agency (ANA)